      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Your code is leaking memory because you allocate a new `OrderData` object inside the loop with `new` but never free it, while also accidentally copying the data from the input vector. The fix is to use a `std::unique_ptr` (or `std::shared_ptr` if you need shared ownership) so that the memory is automatically freed when the pointer goes out of scope. Here is the corrected version:\n\n```cpp\nvoid processOrders(std::vector<OrderData*> orders) {\n    for (size_t i = 0; i < orders.size(); ++i) {\n        // Use unique_ptr for automatic memory management\n        std::unique_ptr<OrderData> currentOrder = std::make_unique<OrderData>(orders[i].id, orders[i].price);\n        \n        if (currentOrder->isValid()) {\n            executeTrade(currentOrder.get());\n        }\n        // No manual delete needed; unique_ptr handles cleanup.\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThis change ensures that every `OrderData` allocated in the loop is properly deallocated after the loop body finishes, eliminating the memory leak.",
